{{Infobox language |name=Chuukese |altname =Trukese |nativename=Chuuk |states=[[Federated States of Micronesia]] |region=[[Chuuk State|Chuuk]] |speakers=51,330 |ethnicity=[[Chuukese people]] |date=2000 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Micronesian languages|Micronesian]] |fam5=Nuclear Micronesian |fam6=[[Trukic-Ponapeic languages|Chuukic-Pohnpeic]] |fam7=[[Trukic languages|Chuukic]] |nation={{flag|Federated States of Micronesia}} |iso2=chk |iso3=chk |glotto=chuu1238 |glottorefname=Chuukese }}
'''Chuukese''' {{IPAc-en|tʃ|uː|ˈ|k|iː|z}}, also rendered '''Trukese''' {{IPAc-en|t|r|ʌ|ˈ|k|iː|z}},<ref>Laurie Bauer, 2007, ''The Linguistics Student's Handbook'', Edinburgh</ref> is a [[Trukic languages|Trukic language]] of the [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian language family]] spoken primarily on the islands of [[Chuuk State|Chuuk]] in the [[Caroline Islands]] in [[Federated States of Micronesia|Micronesia]]. There are communities of speakers on [[Pohnpei]], [[Guam]], and the Hawai'ian Islands as well. Estimates show that there are about 45,900 speakers in Micronesia.<ref name="e18"/>
==Phonology== Chuukese has the unusual feature of permitting word-initial [[geminate]] (double) consonants. The common ancestor of Western Micronesian languages is believed to have had this feature, but most of its modern descendants have lost it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Reflexes of initial gemination in Western Micronesian languages |publisher=[[University of California, Los Angeles]] |url=http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/AFLA12/abstracts/AFLA_0430_B_1200.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=8 September 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6J8wbBbBh?url=http://www.linguistics.ucla.edu/afla12/abstracts/AFLA_0430_B_1200.pdf |archivedate=August 25, 2013 |deadurl=yes |df= }} </ref>
''Truk'' and ''Chuuk'' are a difference in orthography, and both older ''tr'' and current ''ch'' transcribe the sound {{IPAblink|tʂ}}.
