'''Sandha bhasha''', the "language of twilight" ({{lang-hi|संधा भाषा}}), is a [[literary style]] used to express inter-instrumental cognition{{what|date=February 2015}} by [[Siddha]] people. In Sandha, symbols{{what|date=February 2015}} are used to present inter-instrumental expressions{{what|date=February 2015}}.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sandhabhasa |url=http://ccbs.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-ENG/bhasan.htm |publisher=Digital Library & Museum of Buddhist Studies|date=|author=Vidhushekhara Bhattacharya|accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Seeking Bauls of Bengal|author=Jeanne Openshaw|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2002|isbn=9780521811255|page=66|url=http://www.cambridge.org/us/academic/subjects/anthropology/social-and-cultural-anthropology/seeking-bauls-bengal }}</ref> Most of the literature written in Sandha style by the Siddha people are in [[Apabhraṃśa]].{{dubious|date=February 2015}}{{fix|text=The sources suggest it's Bengali or related to Bengali}}

